00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:13.000
And I got to see the land where the blues was born and was really blown away by it because it was, you know, I'm from New Mexico.

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:20.000
And so my father was a, I'm a foreman on the train line.

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:28.000
And so I was around a lot of that work music that you guys documented in the land where the blues was born.

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:41.000
So just that lining up the trains and then just in including all that kind of stuff that was the environmental sounds with your music itself was really showed in me.

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:47.000
Because that's the work, the kind of world I was around as a kid.

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:58.000
So to start out with my life, my grandfather and my mom and a whole family set were migrant farmers.

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:08.000
And my grandfather was a kind of a lighter skinned black man and he could glass as a Latino when he wanted to.

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:14.000
He worked in Mexico, Texas, Oklahoma, New Mexico, Arizona.

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:20.000
And then their migratory parent was always that following the lines to Bakersfield here.

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:22.000
Where was he born or was he born?

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:26.000
Texas. Texas was the part of the life that there were from.

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:34.000
And they traveled with it. It was two men and a woman and they could do everything. They could build houses.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:41.000
I was very empowered with my grandfather's capacity to do things and he had never even, he didn't even have a formal education.

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:46.000
He bought up a lot of property in the town that he settled in.

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:49.000
And the only reason he settled this is tent burned down.

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:54.000
They had to stay there in that town and they figured out how to make it work.

00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:59.000
And so a lot of my grandfather I find as I get older is a lot in me.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:05.000
Because he was my babysitter and he was a power broker.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:10.000
Because I remember walking behind him meeting the mayor.

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:17.000
I had real clear access to going to City Hall and just walking there as a baby.

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:25.000
I can just still, you know, like just so that whole part of a small town and accessibility and things like that.

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:31.000
I was able to see. Also the academy, my grandfather was a projectionist.

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:37.000
And he projected in a town that had the Latino separated from the whites.

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:44.000
So there was a Latino theater that he projected at and then he would run across the street and then project the white theater.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:52.000
And then there was a specific place at the time where blacks only kind of had to be at the top in the balcony.

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:55.000
And then there was a lot of work in the community.

00:04:55.000 --> 00:05:00.000
There was a lot of work in the community.

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:05.000
And I started doing research the last few years of my life.

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:07.000
These last few years.

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:15.000
It's been really interesting to deal with the concept of that town because it was name dimming.

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:21.000
And the Crocker family made the woman who married them.

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:23.000
Her maiden name was dimming.

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:37.000
And dimming in Mexico was the border between Mexico and the US before the Guadalupe Hildalgo.

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:42.000
So I was so our part of that world was quite unique.

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:49.000
So it was Guadalupe Hildalgo. It was the last main land part of the United States that came in.

00:05:49.000 --> 00:06:00.000
And that Pancho vía, Geronimo, Cochise, the Butterfield Trail.

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:05.000
All those things kind of ran through our town, which is pretty interesting.

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:10.000
And that it was airplanes were first used in war, general purging.

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:17.000
You had to think of this sort of a border place where things are influxing.

00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:20.000
Being defined in that way at an influx.

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:24.000
I think so because I was at the crux of a crazy place of change.

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:26.000
And there was a lot of stories.

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:28.000
It was just a whole lot of stories.

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:33.000
If we just went out in Boy Scouts, the stories where these Indian,

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:40.000
so our guy was almost my scout master was like a nephanographic study.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:44.000
He was geologists and waste because he would go out and he was like,

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:49.000
this is where the Cochise and the military would fight at this pass.

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:52.000
And so I dream about it.

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:57.000
And then this is the way that Geronimo was able to live in the desert

00:06:57.000 --> 00:07:00.000
because we had those types of things around this.

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:05.000
And so there was a bunch of people who were like,

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:10.000
you know, Pancho Villa and Zapata were the Latino people that they really liked him a whole lot.

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:15.000
And so there was, and then my grandfather was a baseball fanatic.

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:18.000
And so he had a colored team.

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:25.000
So he had Indians, Asians, blacks, all plain throughout the Southwest as a baseball team.

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:28.000
So there was that kind of bomb storming.

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:29.000
That kind of environment.

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:30.000
So yeah.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:34.000
They played against other colored groups.

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:39.000
There was this whole circuit that they had that were semi-professionals.

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:44.000
And it was a part of the before they became, you know, when they were really segregated.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:49.000
So it was the tail end of all that segregated time period that I was able to see.

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:51.000
That's fast and absolutely fast.

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:54.000
And this would be throughout the Southwest.

00:07:54.000 --> 00:08:00.000
Yeah, because I see my grandfather's pattern would be Texas up to northern New Mexico.

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:06.000
And then what would be Eastern Arizona?

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:09.000
So that was their plain pattern.

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:15.000
And they had their own designations of what the different levels were.

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:21.000
And then after some of our guys would then go to the semi-pro leagues and then, you know,

00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:23.000
kind of work themselves up.

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:26.000
And it was fun to watch them pretty famous.

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:28.000
They were famous within their own world.

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:33.000
Coming in after church, someone would be dressed up in a suit still.

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:38.000
Because they're late on time, you know, late before, but the game got started.

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:39.000
Just be like the pitcher.

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:43.000
I remember the pitcher coming out with this tie on, tucking it around his neck,

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:48.000
and then coming like throwing the shit so hard.

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:52.000
It was just a kind of a fun environment to see these men.

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:59.000
The other part of my life that was interesting is really to me is that I was a designated driver for my grandfather.

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:04.000
My father was an interesting man because he was a foreman.

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:06.000
That's how he got to New Mexico.

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:09.000
And he was a highly intelligent man.

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:14.000
He was born in Des Moines, Iowa.

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:17.000
His family was middle-class. He went to church.

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:20.000
He went to Catholic schools and all that.

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:28.000
He got all the way up to college and went to what is it?

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:31.000
Marquette University.

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:35.000
So he was that kind of a cat and living in that type of a world,

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:41.000
which was, you know, with mostly migrant folks and, you know, kind of pioneering types.

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:45.000
People who migrated to New Mexico were people who were just pioneers.

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:48.000
You know, they just went out and struck out on their own.

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:54.000
And so I got to see the blues being made in just by just really everyday people, you know.

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:57.000
So got to see that and was really pretty impressed.

00:09:57.000 --> 00:10:01.000
And storytellers, I got to meet some really phenomenal storytellers,

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:04.000
the ones that did the signifying monkeys and all that kind of stuff.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:08.000
And got to hear that live and well and was really blown away with it as a kid.

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:13.000
Because I remember trying to describe it, but then the closest I could come was, you know,

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:19.000
that one that Disney did with Uncle, that's what Uncle Remus said.

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:23.000
But these cats were like, they would drink and, you know, like, grab a rattlesnake.

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:28.000
And really I saw a guy grab a rattlesnake and kill the motherfucker while he was telling the story.

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:31.000
So it was that kind of realness around my life, you know.

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:36.000
So he's telling signifying monkey and then this sidewinder comes up and then he's like, grabs it and then like,

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:41.000
and then he is a kid. I was like, how fantastic.

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:45.000
That's a storytelling and half there.

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:51.000
But in the railroad line.

00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:54.000
And that was the other thing I looked up in my life.

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:57.000
I lived some of my formal life in the boxcar.

00:10:57.000 --> 00:11:00.000
So it was kind of like a boxcar.

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:07.000
I remember having those first steps that made a metal, you know, grabbing my arms,

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:12.000
going up the chair, up to get into the boxcar.

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:16.000
And pretty impressed about, you know, so that was part of my life.

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:21.000
So that's the early life and then you said you were designated driver for my dad.

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:23.000
Yeah, that was by the time I turned 16.

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:27.000
But I think that the whole thing on silver rights, the thing that I really,

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:33.000
in New Mexico, it was a cuss, a real cuss, cuss, but change there.

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:38.000
Because at that time, like I was saying, they had things that were still segregated

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:45.000
because the Latinos had their thing and then there was whites and blacks together on the theater level.

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:48.000
And what just interrupt, what year were you born?

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:49.000
In 1945.

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:52.000
1945. So we're talking about when you were saying that those times.

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:57.000
In the 1950s, early 50s from 45.

00:11:57.000 --> 00:12:04.000
Yeah, because it was like, since he was, I would, he babysitted me for the early parts of my life.

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:17.000
So I would say from 1945, until 1955, is where I spent the greater part of like kicking it with him in part in 10 years, you know, for those 10 years.

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:25.000
And then later our family still got engaged with the theater because then my grandfather then projected for the drive in movies.

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:27.000
So he was a part of that too.

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:34.000
And so we could go and see those. So I was always around the kind of movie world and all its manifestations, you know.

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:37.000
Never thought it would be a part of my life.

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:40.000
So just the whole thing of how it happened to me later.

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:43.000
But let's see.

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:46.000
So school.

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:59.000
My first days of school were really, pretty interesting because I had learned to actually, I was a pretty free running kid because it was a free space.

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:06.000
And so the first days of school, I really, when they had recess and things, I disappeared.

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:12.000
And so, and then they found out that I was leaving and going home because I was like, why is everybody sleeping?

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:16.000
I'm not sleeping. So I'm like, I'll just go. And so I just went and went home.

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:18.000
And so they discovered that I was going.

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:23.000
And so I stayed my first recess was after I'd been in school for about a week or two.

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:32.000
And then all the kids all sudden noticed that I was there because they had done this kind of.

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:42.000
What did they call it when they cut places up and only make it like they had the Latinos all in one school and segregated the place.

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:45.000
And so, and then they made Smith school only for white.

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:50.000
And I happened to be one block on this side of the track. It's to the one block on the other.

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:53.000
And so I showed up in school. We kind of white freak them out.

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:56.000
And so the whole.

00:13:56.000 --> 00:14:00.000
In all white school. So I was the only white person in all white school.

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:06.000
And it happened through just the line I happened to be on one side of the railroad track instead of this.

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:09.000
And so when I showed up, the school freaked out.

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:18.000
And, and the kids started throwing rocks at me and throwing dirt and just being pretty just like living their parents life on me.

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:27.000
And, and so I, I then ran. And then later I'd learn to fight for myself because my, my, my cousin was watching me.

00:14:27.000 --> 00:14:31.000
And he looked at me kind of like evilly like, what, you know, just running from these.

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:34.000
You know how to fight. We touchy out of box and stuff.

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:39.000
So I just turned around. And then the funniest thing I still remember is that they says,

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:44.000
oh, you fight like me and you kick like a Mexican.

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:51.000
I said, definitely what come with it.

00:14:51.000 --> 00:15:00.000
And so from then on, I was a jock. I learned how to play football. And I would run over all those kids that, that, that really met me harm.

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:05.000
And so, and I found out how to do it with gusto. And, and I became a jock.

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:11.000
And so my next 12 years was really pretty cool in, in, in New Mexico.

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:13.000
Did that earn you some sort of status or respect?

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:23.000
Very much so. The whole thing. Even throughout because you know it's pioneered pioneering people and they ride horses and, and bronco bulls.

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:31.000
And the whole way that they lived was very rough and ready. And, and I like those guys. You know, they were fun friends of ours.

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:37.000
And my grandfather was a, was a, you know, a bramable. He liked the bramables and all that whole world.

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:42.000
And so we'd watch that. So we had friends that were in the kind of cowboy rodeo world too.

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:50.000
But, and, but with those folks, we just found the same thing. I had to teach my brothers the same thing as they grew up.

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:54.000
Is that, you know, as long as you stood up for yourself, they respect you.

00:15:54.000 --> 00:16:01.000
And so, that was the thing that each of them. And so it was funny. My youngest one we were talking about it as I grew up.

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:03.000
Maybe we should, is, it's all the door.

00:16:03.000 --> 00:16:05.000
Okay. Let me just talk.

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:09.000
We're going again.

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:10.000
Okay.

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:16.000
Okay. I guess I was just talking about that early life of mine.

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:22.000
And, I mean, where, where there are other black families in the town?

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:27.000
Yeah, there was about 150 blacks in the town on a constant basis.

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:36.000
And they were mostly migrant people, really wonderful people, very down the earth.

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:42.000
They treated my family really well.

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:51.000
I've always got, we always got a kind of a real, people treated us nice all of our family, you know, like the black people.

00:16:51.000 --> 00:16:58.000
You know, like the black neighborhoods really treated us really like royal. They treated us very nice, you know.

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:06.000
They like my father. He was highly intelligent man. We were a whole family.

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:12.000
And, and we're proud family.

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:16.000
Oh, that sounds like a serious wreck.

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:22.000
I'll just start with after that was kind of like my child life.

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:24.000
And then I'm asking one more question.

00:17:24.000 --> 00:17:25.000
Sure.

00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:28.000
You started to talk about passing these lessons on to your brothers.

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:29.000
Right.

00:17:29.000 --> 00:17:42.000
And with my brothers, what was interesting is like each of them had to deal with this idea of the pioneering white man.

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:49.000
And then you know, how do you deal with that and their idea of what a black male is, you know.

00:17:49.000 --> 00:17:56.000
And so part of what we, my father taught first was the sense of pride.

00:17:56.000 --> 00:17:59.000
And you all stand up for each other and kind of thing.

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:03.000
And then my sister, we had one sister too. And she was the same kind of person.

00:18:03.000 --> 00:18:08.000
So we didn't stand for the inward. It was like you say it.

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:12.000
And you, your head was off. You know, that was our first concept.

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:21.000
And my father was very much that type of a person. He really did not like cow-tailing to people because of race.

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:27.000
He didn't stand for it a little bit. And he didn't want us to ever be that kind of a person.

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:32.000
So that was the way we were taught. It's like you're a man just like everybody else.

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:36.000
And that really helped us a lot in pioneering towns.

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:40.000
So then you had to keep proving that.

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:46.000
Well, you only have to do it per generation.

00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:53.000
It's like they'll test a call the well the next one and see if you stand up like your brother did and stuff like that.

00:18:53.000 --> 00:19:00.000
And then the process of if they did whip you, then they had to deal with your other brothers.

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:09.240
a thing is part of what we had as a family, a group of boys and girl because my sister

00:19:09.240 --> 00:19:16.080
was as strong as any of the guys that were around.

00:19:16.080 --> 00:19:23.760
And so for instance my brother and I were talking and I was like, because I got drafted.

00:19:23.760 --> 00:19:32.720
So my youngest brother was like four or five years old when I first, well no he was about

00:19:32.720 --> 00:19:34.440
eight, nine, ten years old.

00:19:34.440 --> 00:19:40.720
And then so when I came back he was about to go to junior high to college and I mean high

00:19:40.720 --> 00:19:42.600
school in those days.

00:19:42.600 --> 00:19:48.120
And so anyway so I was not around his life for about eight years and so he came and lived

00:19:48.120 --> 00:19:53.080
with me in DC and so we were just discussing you know, how did you deal with that incident

00:19:53.080 --> 00:19:58.880
